He was doubtless a kinsman of John Frederici († p. 1484), curate of Zeerijp, from whom 116 inherited some books. For many years he was in Italy with Rud. By 1477 he was M.A. and D.M., and secretary to the town of Groningen, and in 1484-5 116 became curate of St. Martin's church: see Α. Gr. Roos, Cataloqus der Inczmabelen of Groningen Univ. Library, 1912, nos. 18, 34, 90, 139. For forty years he held a dominating position in the town, guiding its internai affairs, and by his eloquence playing the chief part in its diplomacy: see Ubbo Emmius’ Rerum Frisicarum Historia, Leiden, 1616. He retired from his cure at StsMartin’s in 1525 and passed his two remaining years in the house of his son (l. 111) at Groningen.
